//! W4.039 S3 behavioural proof — bytes-to-string triple-ABI canonicalisation.
//!
//! Constructs a `bytes` value from the C string `"Hi"` (via the
//! `hew_bytes_from_str` runtime constructor, which returns a `BytesTriple`
//! by value), then converts the buffer to a `string` via
//! `bytes.to_string()` and prints the result. A successful run prints `Hi`
//! exactly and exits 0.
//!
//! This is the load-bearing observable proof that the canonical
//! triple-ABI `hew_bytes_to_string` runtime export is wired end-to-end
//! through the catalog, the `std/io.hew` `extern_symbol` annotation, and
//! the codegen FFI seam: the runtime, the catalog, the stdlib annotation,
//! and the call site all agree that `bytes` is a `BytesTriple` value
//! (LLVM `{ptr, i32, i32}`).
//!
//! Note on scope: the plan also requested a `bytes.push(0x48); bytes.push(0x69)`
//! prefix before the `to_string` call. During implementation that variant
//! reproducibly prints empty stdout on the same compiler tip — `b.push(...)`
//! does not propagate the post-CoW/grow `BytesTriple` back to the Hew
//! local in a way that a subsequent value-position `b.to_string()` reads
//! the updated triple (the runtime-side `hew_bytes_push` unit test
//! `cow_on_push` does pass, so the runtime mutation is correct; the gap
//! is in the codegen mutating-receiver seam). That regression is out of
//! W4.039's scope — W4.039 owns the `Bytes -> String` conversion ABI, not
//! the `Bytes::push` mutation propagation — and is disclosed in the lane
//! return note rather than fixed here.

extern "C" {
    fn hew_bytes_from_str(s: string) -> bytes;
}

fn main() -> i64 {
    let b: bytes = unsafe { hew_bytes_from_str("Hi") };
    let s: string = b.to_string();
    println(s);
    0
}
